# 🚀 FutureOS — Render Deployment Guide

## Architecture on Render
```
[Frontend (React)]  →  [Backend (Spring Boot)]  →  [AI Service (FastAPI)]
                              ↓
                      [MySQL (Managed)]
```

Each service is deployed as a **separate Render Web Service** using Docker.

---

## Step 1 — Push to GitHub

Render deploys from a Git repo. Push your project:

```bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "chore: prepare for Render deployment"
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/FutureOS.git
git push -u origin main
```

---

## Step 2 — Create Render Account

Go to https://render.com and sign up (free tier available).

---

## Step 3 — Deploy Using Blueprint (Recommended)

1. In Render dashboard → click **"New"** → **"Blueprint"**
2. Connect your GitHub repo
3. Render will detect `render.yaml` automatically
4. Click **"Apply"** — Render will create all 3 services + the MySQL database

---

## Step 4 — Set Secret Environment Variables

After blueprint applies, go into each service and set these secrets:

### futureos-ai service:
| Variable | Value |
|----------|-------|
| `GROQ_API_KEY` | Your Groq key from https://console.groq.com (FREE) |
| `OPENAI_API_KEY` | Your OpenAI key (fallback, optional) |

**Groq is recommended** — it's free and faster than OpenAI for this use case.  
Model `llama-3.3-70b-versatile` is already configured in `render.yaml`.

---

## Step 5 — Update Service URLs After First Deploy

After your first deploy, Render assigns public URLs like:
- `https://futureos-ai.onrender.com`
- `https://futureos-backend.onrender.com`
- `https://futureos-frontend.onrender.com`

You **must** update two places:

### In render.yaml (then re-deploy):
```yaml
# Backend service — AI_BASE_URL:
value: https://futureos-ai.onrender.com   # ← your actual AI service URL

# Frontend service — VITE_API_BASE:
value: https://futureos-backend.onrender.com/api  # ← your actual backend URL
```

**OR** set them directly in the Render dashboard under each service's Environment tab.

---

## Step 6 — Database Initialization

The MySQL database on Render (PlanetScale or Render's managed MySQL) will be empty.  
Spring Boot auto-creates tables via `ddl-auto: update` on first boot.

If you want demo data, connect to the DB and run:
```bash
# Get the connection string from Render dashboard → futureos-mysql → Connect
mysql -h <host> -u futureos -p futureos < database/schema.sql
```

---

## Deploy Order (Render handles this automatically)

1. MySQL database (starts first)
2. futureos-ai (FastAPI)
3. futureos-backend (Spring Boot — waits for DB)
4. futureos-frontend (React)

---

## ⚠️ Free Tier Limitations

Render's **free tier services sleep after 15 minutes of inactivity**.  
This means the first request after idle takes ~30–60 seconds to wake up.

**Solution options:**
- Upgrade to **Starter plan** ($7/month per service) to avoid sleep
- Use a cron job / uptime monitor to ping `/health` every 10 minutes

